\n| 1992\n| Rebekka\n| Riga: Riya\n|-\n| Russian\n|\n| 1992\n| Rebekka: roman\n| Izhevsk: Krest\n|-\n| Russian\n|\n| 1992\n| Rebekka\n| Moskva. Dom\n|-\n| Russian\n|\n| 1992\n| Rebekka: roman\n| Kiev: Muza\n|-\n| German\n|\n| 1940\n| Rebecca: Roman\n| Hamburg: Deutsch Hausbucherei\n|-\n| German\n|\n| 1940\n| Rebecca: Roman\n| Saarbr\u00fccken: Clubder Buchfreunde\n|-\n| German\n|\n| 1946\n| Rebecca: Roman\n| Hamburg: Wolfgang Kruger\n|-\n| German\n|\n| 1994\n| Rebecca: Roman\n| Wien: E. Kaiser\n|-\n| 8 other German editions\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| Portuguese\n|\n| 1977\n| Rebecca, a mulher inesquecivel\n| S\u00e3o Paulo: Companhia Editura Nacional\n|-\n| Spanish\n|\n| 1965\n| Rebeca, una mujer inolvidable\n| Mexico: Editora Latin Americana\n|-\n| Spanish\n|\n| 1969\n| Rebeca\n| Mexico: Eiditorial Diana\n|-\n| Spanish\n|\n| 1971\n| Rebeca\n| Barcelona: Plaza & Jan\u00e9s Editores S.A\n|-\n| Spanish\n|\n| 1976\n| Rebeca\n| Barcelona: Orbis\n|-\n| Spanish\n|\n| 1991\n| Rebeca\n| Madrid: Ediciones La Nave\n|-\n|Swedish\n|Dagny Henschen & Hilda Holmberg; 1970 Gunvor V. Blomqvist\n|1939\n|Rebecca\n|Stockholm: Geber, Tiden\n|-\n|Persian\n|\n|1977\n|Rebecca\n|Tehran: Amir Kabir\n|-\n| Persian\n|\n| 1980\n| Rebecca\n| Iran: Amir Kabir Printing Co.\n|-\n| Persian\n|\n| 1990\n| Ribika\n| Tehran: Nashr-i Jahnnama\n|-\n| Hungarian\n| Ruzitska M\u00e1ria\n|\n| A Manderley h\u00e1z asszonya\n| Singer \u00e9s Wolfner Irodalmi Int\u00e9zet Rt.\n|-\n| Hungarian\n| Ruzitska M\u00e1ria\n| 1986\n| A Manderley h\u00e1z asszonya\n| Eur\u00f3pa K\u00f6nyvkiad\u00f3\n|-\n| Hungarian\n| Ruzitska M\u00e1ria\n| 2011\n| A Manderley h\u00e1z asszonya\n| Gabo\n|-\n| Romanian\n|\n| 1993\n| Rebecca: Roman\n| Bucuresti: Editura Orizonturi\n|-\n| Romanian\n| Mihnea Columbeanu\n| 2012\n| Rebecca\n| Bucuresti: Editura Orizonturi\n|-\n| Polish\n| Eleonora Romanowicz\n| 1958<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alpha.bn.org.pl/search~S5*pol?/trebeka/trebeka/1,14,47,B/frameset&FF=trebeka&15,,26|title=Rebeka|first1=Daphne|last1=Du Maurier|first2=Eleonora|last2=Romanowicz-Podoska|date=10 May 2018|publisher=Iskry|via=alpha.bn.org.pl Library Catalog}}</ref>\n| Rebeka\n| Warszawa: Iskry\n|-\n| Greek\n|\n| 1960\n| Revekka: mytgustirema\n| Athenai: Ekdosies Dem, Darema\n|-\n| Latvian\n|\n| 1972\n| Rebeka: romans\n| Bruklina: Gramatudraugs\n|-\n| Dutch\n|\n| 1941\n| Rebecca\n| Leiden: AW Sijthoff\n|-\n|Czech\n|\n| 1939\n| Mrtv\u00e1 a \u017div\u00e1: [Rebeka]\n| Praha: Evropsk\u00fd liter\u00e1rn\u00ed klub\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards==\nIn the US, du Maurier won the [[List of National Book Award winners#1935 to 1941|National Book Award]] for favourite novel of 1938, voted by members of the [[American Booksellers Association]].<ref name=\"nyt1939\">{{Citation|title=Book About Plants Receives Award: Dr. Fairchild's 'Garden' Work Cited by Booksellers|newspaper=The New York Times|date=15 February 1939|page=20|publisher=ProQuest Historical Newspapers 1851\u20132007|quote=Du Maurier participating in the [[Hotel Astor]] luncheon by transatlantic telephone from London to New York. She called for writers and distributors to offset, in the literary world, the contemporary trials of civilization in the political world.}}</ref> In 2003, the novel was listed at number 14 on the UK survey [[The Big Read]].<ref>{{Citation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100.shtml|publisher=BBC|title=The Big Read|date=April 2003|accessdate=19 October 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031065136/http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100.shtml|archivedate=31 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was voted the UK's favourite book of the past 225 years in a poll by bookseller [[W H Smith]]. Other novels in the shortlist were ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird]]'' by [[Harper Lee]], ''[[Pride and Prejudice]]'' by [[Jane Austen]], ''[[Jane Eyre]]'' by [[Charlotte Bronte]], and ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four|1984]]'' by [[George Orwell]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/whsmith-names-rebecca-nations-favourite-book-562661|publisher=The Bookseller|title=W H Smith names Rebecca the nation's favourite book|date=June 2017|accessdate=2 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606083837/http://www.thebookseller.com/news/whsmith-names-rebecca-nations-favourite-book-562661|archivedate=6 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}.</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n===Film===\n''Rebecca'' has been adapted for film several times. The best known of these is the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]\u2013winning 1940 [[Alfred Hitchcock]] film version ''[[Rebecca (1940 film)|Rebecca]]'', the first film Hitchcock made under his contract with [[David O. Selznick]]. The film, which starred [[Laurence Olivier]] as Max, [[Joan Fontaine]] as the heroine, and [[Judith Anderson]] as Mrs Danvers, was based on the novel. However, the Hollywood [[Motion Picture Production Code|Production Code]] required that if Max had murdered his wife, he would have to be punished for his crime. Therefore, the key turning point of the novel&nbsp;\u2013 the revelation that Max, in fact, murdered Rebecca&nbsp;\u2013 was altered so that it seemed as if Rebecca's death was accidental. At the end of the film version, Mrs Danvers perishes in the fire, which she had started. The film quickly became a classic and, at the time, was a major technical achievement in film-making.{{Citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nThe 1964 [[Bollywood]] Hindi film ''[[Kohra]]'' and the 2008 film ''[[Anamika (2008 film)|Anamika]]'' were inspired by ''Rebecca''.\n\nAn upcoming film adaptation, ''[[Rebecca (upcoming film)|Rebecca]]'', was directed by [[Ben Wheatley]] and written by [[Jane Goldman]], and stars [[Lily James]] and [[Armie Hammer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/lily-james-armie-hammer-rebecca-movie-director-ben-wheatley-1202502252/|title=Deadline|archivedate=14 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\n[[File:DaphneDuMaurier Rebecca.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Pan UK paperback edition cover (showing [[Joanna David]] as Mrs de Winter from the BBC television production. Jeremy Brett played the role of Maxim de Winter.)]]\n\n''Rebecca'' was adapted for ''[[The Philco Television Playhouse]]'' (October 10, 1948), with [[Mary Anderson (actress, born 1918)|Mary Anderson]] and [[Bramwell Fletcher]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ctva.biz/US/Anthology/PhilcoTelevisionPlayhouse_01_%281948-49%29.htm |title=Philco Television Playhouse  |publisher=Classic Television Archive |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]'' (May 22, 1950), with [[Barbara Bel Geddes]] and [[Peter Cookson]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ctva.biz/US/Anthology/RobertMontgomeryPresents_01_%28Early1950%29.htm |title=Robert Montgomery Presents  |publisher=Classic Television Archive |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Broadway Television Theatre]]'' (September 1, 1952), with [[Patricia Breslin]] and [[Scott Forbes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ctva.biz/US/Anthology/BroadwayTelevisionTheatre_01_%28Early1952%29.htm |title=Broadway Television Theatre  |publisher=Classic Television Archive |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Theatre '62]]'' presented an NBC-TV adaptation starring [[James Mason]] as Maxim, [[Joan Hackett]] as the second Mrs. de Winter, and [[Nina Foch]] as Mrs. Danvers.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0056398/combined Rebecca (1962) (TV)], Internet Movie Database. Retrieved October 8, 2013.</ref>\n\n''[[Rebecca (1979 miniseries)|Rebecca]]'', a 1979<!-- broadcast in the UK from 19 January. --> [[BBC]] adaptation, was directed by Simon Langton and starred [[Jeremy Brett]] as Maxim, [[Joanna David]] as the second Mrs de Winter, and [[Anna Massey]] (Jeremy Brett's former wife) as Mrs Danvers. It ran for four 55-minute episodes. It was broadcast in the United States on [[PBS]] as part of its ''[[Mystery!]]'' series.\n\n''[[Rebecca (miniseries)|Rebecca]]'', a 1997 [[Carlton Television]] miniseries, starred [[Emilia Fox]] (Joanna David's daughter, in the same role played by her mother in 1979), [[Charles Dance]] as de Winter, and Dame [[Diana Rigg]] as Mrs Danvers. It was directed by Jim O'Brien, with a screenplay by Arthur Hopcraft. It was broadcast in the United States by PBS as part of its ''[[Masterpiece Theatre]]'' series. This adaptation is noteworthy for featuring an appearance by Rebecca, played by [[Lucy Cohu]]. It also shows Maxim saving Mrs Danvers from the fire, ending with an epilogue showing Maxim and the second Mrs de Winter relaxing abroad, as she explains what she and Maxim do with their days now they are unlikely ever to return to Manderley.\n\nThe 2009 Pakistani drama series ''[[Noorpur Ki Rani]]'' was based on ''Rebecca''.\n\n===Radio===\nThe first adaptation of ''Rebecca'' for any medium was presented 9 December 1938, by [[Orson Welles]], as the debut program of his live [[CBS Radio]] series, ''[[The Campbell Playhouse (radio series)|The Campbell Playhouse]]'' (the sponsored continuation of ''[[The Mercury Theatre on the Air]]''). Introducing the story, Welles refers to the forthcoming motion picture adaptation by David O. Selznick; at the conclusion of the show he interviews Daphne du Maurier in London via [[shortwave radio]]. The novel was adapted by [[Howard E. Koch]].<ref name=\"TIOW\">[[Orson Welles|Welles, Orson]], and [[Peter Bogdanovich]], edited by [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]], ''[[This is Orson Welles]]''. New York: [[HarperCollins]] Publishers 1992 {{ISBN|0-06-016616-9}}</ref>{{Rp|348}} Welles and [[Margaret Sullavan]] starred as Max de Winter and the second Mrs de Winter. Other cast included [[Mildred Natwick]] (Mrs Danvers), [[Ray Collins (actor)|Ray Collins]] (Frank Crawley), [[George Coulouris]] (Captain Searle), [[Frank Readick]] (as Ben), Alfred Shirley (Frith), Eustace Wyatt (Coroner) and [[Agnes Moorehead]] (Mrs Van Hopper).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://orsonwelles.indiana.edu/items/show/1975 |title=The Campbell Playhouse: Rebecca |website=Orson Welles on the Air, 1938\u20131946 |publisher=[[Indiana University Bloomington]] |access-date=2018-07-30 }}</ref><ref name=\"Goldin Campbell\">{{cite web|url=http://radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=The+Campbell+Playhouse|title=The Campbell Playhouse|publisher=RadioGOLDINdex|accessdate=2014-11-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206050605/http://radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=The+Campbell+Playhouse|archivedate=6 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Bernard Herrmann]] composed and conducted the score, which later formed the basis of his score for the 1943 film, ''[[Jane Eyre (1943 film)|Jane Eyre]]''.<ref name=\"Smith\">Smith, Steven C., ''A Heart at Fire's Center: The Life and Music of Bernard Herrmann''. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1991 {{ISBN|0-520-07123-9}}</ref>{{Rp|67}}\n\n''[[The Screen Guild Theater]]'' presented half-hour adaptions with Joan Fontaine, her husband at the time [[Brian Aherne]], and [[Agnes Moorehead]] (May 31, 1943), and with [[Loretta Young]], [[John Lund (actor)|John Lund]] and Agnes Moorehead (November 18, 1948).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/ScreenGuildTheater |title=Screen Guild Theater  |publisher=[[Internet Archive]] |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaldeliftp.com/DigitalDeliToo/dd2jb-Screen-Guild.html |title=The Screen Guild Radio Programs  |publisher=Digital Deli Too |accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> Joan Fontaine and [[Joseph Cotten]] performed a half-hour adaptation October 1, 1946, on ''[[The Cresta Blanca Hollywood Players]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=Cresta+Blanca+Hollywood+Players |title=Cresta Blanca Hollywood Players  |publisher=RadioGOLDINdex |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''The [[Lux Radio Theatre]]'' presented hour-long adaptations with [[Ronald Colman]], [[Ida Lupino]] and Judith Anderson (February 3, 1941), and with Laurence Olivier, [[Vivien Leigh]] and [[Betty Blythe]] (November 6, 1950).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=The+Lux+Radio+Theatre |title=The Lux Radio Theatre  |publisher=RadioGOLDINdex |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Lux15 |title=Lux Radio Theatre 1950  |publisher=Internet Archive |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\nDu Maurier herself adapted ''Rebecca'' as a [[Daphne du Maurier#Plays|stage play]] in 1939; it had a successful London run in 1940 of over 350 performances.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.dumaurier.org/reviews-rebecca.html|contribution=Rebecca|title=Reviews|publisher=du Maurier|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704123152/http://www.dumaurier.org/reviews-rebecca.html|archivedate=4 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}.</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.tcm.turner.com/thismonth/article/?cid=194276|contribution=du Maurier|type=profile|publisher=Turner|title=Classic Movies}}</ref> The Talking Books for the blind edition read by Barbara Caruso borrows heavily from this stage adaptation which differs materially from the novel in many respects including changing the iconic ending of the novel.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Mont\u00e9|first1=Rebecca|editor1-last=Carroll|editor1-first=Rachel|title=Adaptation in Contemporary Culture: Textual Infidelities|date=2009|publisher=Continuum|location=London|isbn=9780826424648|chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=m4Otkfup39wC&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q&f=false|chapter=Origin and Ownership: Film and Television Adaptations of Daphne du Maurier's Rebecca|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180329184501/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=m4Otkfup39wC&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=29 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA Broadway stage adaptation starring [[Diana Barrymore]], [[Bramwell Fletcher]] and [[Florence Reed]] ran January 18 \u2013 February 3, 1945, at the [[Ethel Barrymore Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/Production/View/1666 |title=Rebecca  |publisher=[[Internet Broadway Database]] |accessdate=October 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 September 2006 a musical version of ''[[Rebecca (musical)|Rebecca]]'' premi\u00e8red at the [[Raimund Theater]] in Vienna, Austria. The musical was written by [[Michael Kunze]] (book and lyrics) and [[Sylvester Levay]] (music) and directed by the American director [[Francesca Zambello]]. The cast included [[Uwe Kr\u00f6ger]] as Max de Winter, Wietske van Tongeren as \"Ich\" (\"I\", the narrator) and Susan Rigvava-Dumas as Mrs Danvers. Before 2008 there was talk of moving the musical to the Broadway stage, but the original plans were cancelled due to the complexity of the sets, scenery, and special effects&nbsp;\u2013 including a grand staircase that twirls down into the stage and a finale in which the entire stage&nbsp;\u2013 including Mrs Danvers&nbsp;\u2013 is engulfed in flames. The musical was scheduled to open on Broadway on 18 November 2012, with Jill Paice as \"I\", Ryan Silverman as Max de Winter, and Karen Mason as Mrs Danvers, but funding difficulties led to last-minute cancellation.\n\n===Opera===\n''Rebecca'' was adapted as an opera with music by [[Wilfred Josephs]], premiered by [[Opera North]] in Leeds, England, 15 October 1983.<ref>{{Citation|newspaper=The Times | date =17 October 1983| page = 15, col A|id=article CS252153169}}.</ref>\n\n==Sequels and related works==\nThe novel has inspired three additional books approved by the du Maurier estate:\n* ''[[Mrs. de Winter|Mrs de Winter]]'' (1993) by [[Susan Hill]]. ({{ISBN|978-0-09-928478-9}})\n* ''The Other Rebecca'' (1996) by [[Maureen Freely]]. ({{ISBN|978-0-89733-477-8}})\n* ''Rebecca's Tale'' (2001) by [[Sally Beauman]] ({{ISBN|978-0-06-621108-4}})\n\n==''Rebecca'' as a WWII code key==\nOne edition of the book was used by the Germans in [[World War II]] as the key to a book code.<ref name=\"Eppler\">{{cite web|title=The Real Spy's Story Reads Like Fiction and 40 Years Later Inspires a Best-Seller|first=Pamela|last=Andriotakis|work=People archive|date=15 December 1980|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20078120,00.html|accessdate=28 February 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110110122006/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20078120,00.html|archivedate=10 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sentences would be made using single words in the book, referred to by page number, line and position in the line. One copy was kept at [[Rommel]]'s headquarters,<ref name=\"Eppler\" /> and the other was carried by German [[Abwehr]] agents infiltrated into [[Cairo]] after crossing [[Egypt]] by car, guided by Count [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Alm\u00e1sy]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}} This code was never used, however, because the radio section of the HQ was captured in a skirmish and hence the Germans suspected that the code was compromised.<ref name=\"Eppler2\">{{cite web|title=KV 2/1467|publisher=The National Archives|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/record?catid=8424225&catln=6|accessdate=28 February 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414015049/http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/record?catid=8424225&catln=6|archivedate=14 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This use of the book is referred to in [[Ken Follett]]'s novel ''[[The Key to Rebecca]]''&nbsp;\u2013 where a (fictional) spy does use it to pass critical information to Rommel.<ref name=\"Follett\">{{cite web|title=The Key to Rebecca|work=Ken Follett|url=http://ken-follett.com/bibliography/the_key_to_rebecca/|accessdate=28 February 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130110080641/http://ken-follett.com/bibliography/the_key_to_rebecca/|archivedate=10 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThis use of the novel was also referred to in [[Michael Ondaatje]]'s 1992 novel ''[[The English Patient]]''.<ref name=\"Spark\">{{cite web|title=The English Patient \u2013 Chapter VI|work=Spark Notes|url=http://www.sparknotes.com/lit/englishpatient/section6.rhtml|accessdate=28 February 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527235249/http://www.sparknotes.com/lit/englishpatient/section6.rhtml|archivedate=27 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe novel, and the character of [[Mrs. Danvers|Mrs Danvers]] in particular, have entered many aspects of popular culture.\n\n===Literature===\nThe character of Mrs Danvers is alluded to numerous times throughout [[Stephen King]]'s ''[[Bag of Bones]]''. In the book, Mrs Danvers serves as something of a [[bogeyman]] for the main character Mike Noonan. King also uses the character name for the chilly, obedient servant in \"Father's Day\", a tale in his 1982 film ''[[Creepshow]]''.\n\nIn [[Jasper Fforde]]'s ''[[Thursday Next]]'' series, in the bookworld, they have accidentally made thousands of Mrs Danvers clones, which they use as troops against The Mispeling Vyrus and other threats.\n\nIn ''[[The Maxx]]'' issue No. 31, a teenage Julie Winters watches a black-and-white version of the movie.\n\nIn  ''[[Fifty Shades Darker]]'' by [[E.L. James]], Anastasia Steele reads ''Rebecca'' after an argument with Christian Grey. Anastasia is haunted by Christian's previous relationships with his \"submissives\" and like the second Mrs de Winters, is fearful she doesn't measure up.\n\nIn [[Danielle Steel]]'s novel ''Vanished'', it is mentioned that the main character is reading ''Rebecca''. This was most likely deliberate on Steele's part, considering that the novel has many of the same elements as ''Rebecca''.\n\nIn [[Linda Howard]]'s 2010 novel ''Veil of Night'', Eric compares an assistant to Danvers as well as stating he read the book under protest to pass a high school literature class.\n\n===Film===\nThe 1983 science fiction comedy film ''[[The Man with Two Brains]]'' gives a brief nod to aspects of ''Rebecca.'' After falling for Dolores Benedict, Dr Hfuhruhurr ([[Steve Martin]]) intends to marry her and seeks a sign from the portrait of his deceased wife, Rebecca. The supernatural reaction of the portrait doesn't convince him and so he places her in a cupboard.\n\n===Television===\nThe 1970 Parallel Time storyline of the Gothic soap opera ''[[Dark Shadows]]'' was heavily inspired by ''Rebecca'' including the costume ball scene. Also the second ''Dark Shadows'' motion picture, ''[[Night of Dark Shadows]]'' took inspiration from the novel including a mention by Kate Jackson's character who hopes the housekeeper is not like Mrs Danvers\n\nThe film was parodied on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'' in a 1972 skit called \"Rebecky\", with [[Carol Burnett]] as the heroine, Daphne; [[Harvey Korman]] as Max \"de Wintry\" and in the guise of Mother Marcus as Rebecky de Wintry; and [[Vicki Lawrence]] as Mrs Dampers. The story was again referenced in an episode of the series \"Mama's Family\" (a spinoff of the Burnett show) titled \"I Do, I Don't.\" In it, Bubba, Iola, and Mama each have nightmares about married life. Mama's dream is a parody of the ''Rebecca'' scenario.\n<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1787561 The Carol Burnett Show: Episode No. 6.3 (27 September 1972)], Internet Movie Database. Retrieved October 8, 2013.</ref> \n\nThe fifth episode of the second series of ''[[That Mitchell and Webb Look]]'' contains an extended sketch parodying the 1940 film, in which Rebecca is unable to live up to Maxim's and Mrs Danvers's expectations for the Second Mrs de Winter&nbsp;\u2013 described as \"TBA\".<ref>{{YouTube|Tr59DKnFKx0}}</ref>\n\nThe plots of certain Latin-American soap operas have also been inspired by this story, such as ''Manuela'' (Argentina),<ref>{{cite web|language=Italian|work=Il Mondo dei doppiatori, Zona soup opera e telenovelas|title=Manuela|url=http://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/novelas/manuela.htm|accessdate=28 February 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231054155/http://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/novelas/manuela.htm|archivedate=31 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Infierno en el para\u00edso'' (Mexico),<ref name=\"Univision\">{{cite web|title=Telenovelas A\u2013Z: Infierno en el para\u00edso|language=Spanish|trans-title=Soap operas A\u2013Z: Hell in paradise|work=Univision|url=http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=119523l|accessdate=28 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606004836/http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=119523l|archivedate=6 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the Venezuelan telenovela ''Julia'' and its remake ''[[El Fantasma de Elena]]'' on [[Telemundo]].\n\nIn 1986, an episode of ''[[The Comic Strip Presents]]'' called \"Consuela\" parodied ''Rebecca''. It was written by [[French and Saunders]], and starred Dawn French as the maid and Jennifer Saunders as the new wife of Adrian Edmondson.\n\nIn the episode \"[[Eloise (The Sopranos)|Eloise]]\" from ''[[The Sopranos]]'', Carmella Soprano, while at lunch with her daughter Meadow, speaks disapprovingly of Meadow's relationship with her boyfriend, saying that they \"hang on each other\", to which Meadow replies \"Excuse me, Mrs Danvers, what do you have against love?\"\n\n===Music===\n[[Meg & Dia]]'s Meg Frampton penned a song entitled \"Rebecca\", inspired by the novel.\n\n[[Kansas (band)|Kansas]] alumnus [[Steve Walsh (musician)|Steve Walsh]]'s solo recording ''[[Glossolalia (album)|Glossolalia]]'' includes a song entitled \"Rebecca\", with lyrics seemingly composed from Maxim de Winter's point of view: \"I suppose I was the lucky one, returning like a wayward son to Manderley, I'd never be the same...\".\n\n[[Steve Hackett]] included a song entitled \"Rebecca\", inspired by the novel, on his album ''[[To Watch the Storms]]''.\n\n===Fashion===\nIn 2013, Devon watchmakers Du Maurier Watches, founded by the grandson of Daphne du Maurier, released a limited edition collection of two watches inspired by the characters from the novel&nbsp;\u2013 The Rebecca and The Maxim.<ref>House, Christian. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/10248724/Daphne-du-Maurier-always-said-her-novel-Rebecca-was-a-study-in-jealousy.html \"Daphne du Maurier always said her novel Rebecca was a study in jealousy\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215034135/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/10248724/Daphne-du-Maurier-always-said-her-novel-Rebecca-was-a-study-in-jealousy.html |date=15 February 2018 }}, ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', London, 17 August 2013. Retrieved on 6 October 2013.</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\nOn November 5, 2019, the ''[[BBC News]]'' listed ''Rebecca'' on its list of the [[BBC list of 100 'most inspiring' novels|100 most influential novels]].<ref name=Bbc2019-11-05/>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Bbc2019-11-05>\n{{cite news\n| url         = https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-50302788\n| title       = 100 'most inspiring' novels revealed by BBC Arts\n| work        = [[BBC News]]\n| date        = 2019-11-05\n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2019-11-10\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = The reveal kickstarts the BBC's year-long celebration of literature.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bl.uk/works/rebecca ''Rebecca''] at the British Library\n* {{Citation|url=http://literapedia.wikispaces.com/Rebecca|contribution=Rebecca|type=book notes|title=Literapedia|publisher=Wikispaces}}.\n* {{IMDb title|0032976}}\n* [https://orsonwelles.indiana.edu/items/show/1975 \"Rebecca\"] (9 December 1938) on ''[[The Campbell Playhouse (radio series)|The Campbell Playhouse]]'', with [[Orson Welles]] and [[Margaret Sullavan]] ([[Indiana University Bloomington]])\n\n{{Daphne du Maurier}}\n\n[[Category:1938 British novels]]\n[[Category:Anthony Award-winning works]]\n[[Category:British crime novels]]\n[[Category:British novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:British romance novels]]\n[[Category:British Gothic novels]]\n[[Category:National Book Award for Fiction winning works]]\n[[Category:Novels by Daphne du Maurier]]\n[[Category:Victor Gollancz Ltd books]]\n[[Category:Works about remarriage]]\n[[Category:Works about widowhood]]\n[[Category:Novels involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "use same link throughout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Stalag 17", "text_new": "{{short description|1953 film by Billy Wilder}}\n{{About|the film|the punk band|Stalag 17 (band)}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Stalag 17\n| image          = Stalag 17.jpeg\n| caption        = [[Film poster|Theatrical release poster]]\n| director       = [[Billy Wilder]]\n| producer       = Billy Wilder\n| based on       = ''Stalag 17''<br> by [[Donald Bevan]]<br>[[Edmund Trzcinski]]\n| screenplay     = [[Edwin Blum]]<br/>Billy Wilder\n| narrator       = [[Gil Stratton]]\n| starring       = [[William Holden]]<br>[[Don Taylor (actor)|Don Taylor]]<br>[[Otto Preminger]]\n| music          = [[Franz Waxman]]\n| cinematography = [[Ernest Laszlo]], ASC\n| editing        = [[George Tomasini]]\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1953|5|29|UK, premiere|1953|7|1|US}}\n| runtime        = 120 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1,661,530\n| gross          = $10,000,000\n}}\n\n'''''Stalag 17''''' is a 1953 [[comedy-drama]] [[war film]] which tells the story of a group of [[United States Army Air Forces|American airmen]] held in a [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[World War II]] [[prisoner of war]] camp, who come to suspect that one of their number is an informant. The film was adapted by [[Billy Wilder]] and [[Edwin Blum]] from the [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] play of the same name by [[Donald Bevan]] and [[Edmund Trzcinski]], which was based on their experiences as prisoners in [[Stalag]] 17B in [[Austria]].\n\nProduced and directed by Wilder, it starred [[William Holden]] in his [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning role, [[Don Taylor (actor)|Don Taylor]], [[Robert Strauss (actor)|Robert Strauss]], [[Neville Brand]], [[Harvey Lembeck]], [[Peter Graves (actor)|Peter Graves]], [[Sig Ruman]] and [[Otto Preminger]]. Strauss and Lembeck both appeared in the original Broadway production.\n\nThe 1960s television comedy [[Hogan's Heroes]] was - at least in some part - based on Stalag 17.\n\n==Plot==\n''Stalag 17'' begins on \"the longest night of the year\" in 1944 in a [[Stalag|Luftwaffe prisoner-of-war camp]] somewhere along the [[Danube|Danube River]]. The story is narrated by Clarence Harvey \"Cookie\" Cook. The camp holds Poles, Czechs, Russian women and, in the American compound, 640 sergeants from bomber crews, gunners, radiomen, and flight engineers.\n\nManfredi and Johnson try to escape through a [[escape tunnel|tunnel]], but are shot by waiting guards when they emerge outside the barbed wire fence. The other prisoners conclude that one of their own must have told the Germans. Suspicion falls on Sefton, an enterprising cynic who barters openly with the German guards for eggs, silk stockings, blankets and other luxuries. He also organizes mouse races and various other profitable ventures. Sefton tells the men it is foolish to try to escape.\n\nThe lives of the prisoners are depicted: they receive mail, eat terrible food, wash in the latrine sinks, and collectively do their best to keep sane and defy the camp's commandant, [[Oberst]] [Colonel] von Scherbach. They use a clandestine radio, smuggled from barracks to barracks, to pick up the BBC and the war news.  One German guard, [[Feldwebel]] [Staff Sergeant] Schulz, confiscates the radio in another success for the \"stoolie.\"\n\n\"Animal\" Kuzawa is infatuated with movie star [[Betty Grable]], and becomes depressed when he learns she has married bandleader [[Harry James]]. Harry \"Sugar Lips\" Shapiro gets seven letters at mail call and makes Animal think they are from women. When Kuzawa sees a finance company letterhead, Harry admits they repossessed his [[Plymouth (automobile)|Plymouth]].\n\nSefton bribes the guards to let him spend the day in the Russian women's barracks. The other prisoners conclude that this is his reward for having informed the Germans about the radio. When he returns, he is accused of being a spy.\n\nThen von Scherbach takes Lieutenant James Schuyler Dunbar, a temporary inmate, away. Dunbar admitted to the other prisoners that he had blown up a passing German ammunition train while he was being transported to the camp. Sefton resents Dunbar for coming from a wealthy Boston family. The men are convinced that Sefton betrayed Dunbar, so they beat him up and ostracize him. Sefton then focuses more effort on uncovering the identity of the real spy. During a fake air raid, he remains unnoticed in the evacuated barracks and overhears the barracks security chief, Price, talking with Schulz in German and divulging the means by which Dunbar destroyed the train (a [[matchbook]] with a lit cigarette tucked into the edge to create a time delay). Sefton considers what to do; if he exposes Price, the Germans will simply remove him and plant him in another camp, while killing him could expose the entire barracks to retaliatory execution.\n\nOn Christmas Day, the men find out that [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] men are coming to take Dunbar to Berlin for his sabotage. They create a diversion, free Dunbar, and hide him in the Water Tower. Nobody but Hoffy, the compound chief, knows where he is. The Germans, despite extensive efforts, are unable to find Dunbar. After von Scherbach threatens to raze the camp if necessary, the men decide one of them must get Dunbar out. Price volunteers, but then Sefton accuses him of being a spy. Sefton asks him, \"When was [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor]]?\" Price knows the date, but Sefton quickly asks what time he heard the news. Without thinking, Price answers 6 o'clock and that he was eating dinner \u2014 the correct time in Berlin, but not in Cleveland, Ohio, his claimed hometown. Sefton then reaches into Price's jacket pocket and extracts the \"mailbox\" used to exchange messages with the Germans, a hollowed-out black chess queen.\n\nSefton decides to take Dunbar out himself because he likes the odds this time and the expected reward from Dunbar's family. The men give Sefton enough time to get Dunbar out of the water tower above one of the latrines, then throw Price out into the yard with tin cans tied to his legs. The ruse works: Price is killed in a hail of bullets, creating a diversion that allows Sefton and Dunbar to cut through the barbed wire and escape. A pleased Cookie whistles \"[[When Johnny Comes Marching Home]]\" as things can be seen returning to normal in the barracks.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[William Holden]] as J.J. Sefton\n* [[Don Taylor (actor)|Don Taylor]] as Lieutenant James Dunbar\n* [[Otto Preminger]] as Colonel von Scherbach\n* [[Robert Strauss (actor)|Robert Strauss]] as Stanislas \"Animal\" Kuzawa\n* [[Harvey Lembeck]] as Harry Shapiro\n* [[Peter Graves (actor)|Peter Graves]] as Price\n* [[Sig Ruman]] as Sergeant Johann Sebastian Schulz\n* [[Neville Brand]] as Duke\n* [[Richard Erdman]] as \"Hoffy\" Hoffman\n* Michael Moore as Manfredi\n* [[Peter Baldwin (director)|Peter Baldwin]] as Johnson\n* Robinson Stone as Joey\n* Robert Shawley as \"Blondie\" Peterson\n* [[William Pierson]] as Marko the Mailman\n* [[Gil Stratton]] as Clarence Harvey \"Cookie\" Cook (Narrator)\n* [[Jay Lawrence (actor)|Jay Lawrence]] as Bagradian\n* [[Erwin Kalser]] as Geneva Man\n* [[Edmund Trzcinski]] as himself/\"Triz\"\n* [[Paul Salata]] as Prisoner with Beard (uncredited)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Original Broadway production===\nThe film was adapted by Wilder and [[Edwin Blum]] from the Broadway play by [[Donald Bevan]] and [[Edmund Trzcinski]] which was based on their experiences as prisoners in [[Stalag]] 17B in [[Austria]]. Trzcinski appears in the film as a prisoner.\n\nThe play was directed by [[Jos\u00e9 Ferrer]] and was the Broadway debut of [[John Ericson]] as Sefton. First presented at the Edwin Burke Memorial Theater of [[The Lambs]], a theatrical club, on March 11, 1951 (staged by the authors). It began its Broadway run in May 1951 and continued for 472 performances. The character Sefton was loosely based on Joe Palazzo, a flier in Trzcinski's prisoner-of-war barracks. The script was rewritten extensively by Wilder and Blum.\n\n===Casting===\nBoth [[Charlton Heston]] and [[Kirk Douglas]] were considered for the role of Sefton.<ref name=\"Capua2009\">{{cite book|last=Capua|first=Michelangelo|title=William Holden: A Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uMp6ACb74UkC&pg=PA65|date=9 October 2009|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5550-8|page=65}}</ref>\n\n===Location===\nThe prison camp set was built on the John Show Ranch in [[Woodland Hills, California|Woodland Hills]], on the southwestern edge of the [[San Fernando Valley]].<ref name=\"Rowan\">{{cite book|last=Rowan|first=Terry|title=World War II Goes to the Movies & Television Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OdvGBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA443|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-105-58602-6|page=443}}</ref> The shoot began in February 1952, during the rainy season in California, providing plenty of mud for the camp compound.<ref name=\"Phillips2010\">{{cite book|last=Phillips|first=Gene|title=Some Like It Wilder: The Life and Controversial Films of Billy Wilder|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5uohNoRFkwIC&pg=PT163|date=5 February 2010|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0-8131-7367-1|page=163}}</ref> It is now the location of a [[meetinghouse]] of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]].\n\n===Filming and release===\nThe film was shot in chronological order, an unusual practice as that method is usually much more expensive and time-consuming. In a [[featurette]] released later, members of the cast said that they themselves did not know the identity of the informant until the last three days of shooting.\n\nPeter Graves recalled the film was held from release for over a year due to Paramount Pictures not believing anyone would be interested in seeing a film about prisoners of war. The 1953 release of American POWs from the [[Korean War]] led Paramount to release it on an [[exploitation film|exploitation]] angle.<ref>p.146 Weaver, Tom ''Peter Graves Interview'' in ''Earth Vs. the Sci-fi Filmmakers: 20 Interviews'' McFarland, 1 Jan 2005</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Stalag 17'' was a commercial success. Produced on a budget of $1,661,530, it earned $3.3 million in US [[Gross rental|theatrical rentals]]<ref>'The Top Box Office Hits of 1953', ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', January 13, 1954.</ref> and $10 million in worldwide markets. The film was well received and is considered, along with ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' and ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]'' (also starring Holden), among the best [[World War II]] [[Prisoner of War]] films. [[Bosley Crowther]] praised the film, calling it \"cracker jack movie entertainment\".<ref name=NYTCrowther1953>{{cite news |last=Crowther |first=Bosley |title=TWO NEW FILMS ARRIVE; 'Stalag 17' Emerges as Taut Film With William Holden -- Has Bow at Astor |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C03E7D91F3DE03ABC4A53DFB1668388649EDE |date=July 2, 1953 |department=Movies |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> More recently, film critic [[James Berardinelli]] stated that \"among the 20th century directors, few were more versatile than Billy Wilder\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Berardinelli |first=James |title=Stalag 17 |url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/s/stalag17.html |date= |publisher=[[ReelViews]] |accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> The film currently has a 97% \"Fresh\" rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 31 reviews, and the site's consensus stating: \"''Stalag 17'' survives the jump from stage to screen with flying colors, thanks to Billy Wilder's typically sterling direction and a darkly funny script.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/stalag_17/|title=Stalag 17|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=2 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223022922/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/stalag_17/|archivedate=23 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nHolden won the Academy Award for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]. His acceptance speech is one of the shortest on record (\"thank you, thank you\"); the TV broadcast had a strict cutoff time which forced Holden's quick remarks. The frustrated Holden personally paid for advertisements in the Hollywood trade publications to thank everyone he wanted to on Oscar night. He also remarked that he felt that either [[Burt Lancaster]] or [[Montgomery Clift]] should have won the Best Actor Oscar for ''[[From Here to Eternity]]'' instead of him. It is said that he felt he was given the award as consolation for not having previously won it for ''[[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Sunset Boulevard]]''.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nIn addition, Wilder was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director Oscar]], and Strauss for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]].<ref name=\"Holsinger1999\">{{cite book|last=Holsinger|first=M. Paul|title=War and American Popular Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Oe4AOVHkJ9oC&pg=PA310|year=1999|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-29908-7|page=310}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The television series [[Hogan's Heroes]] (1965 to 1971) is based on a similar [[Stalag]]. \n* \"[[Stalag riddim|Stalag 17]]\" is a 1973 [[reggae]] [[riddim]], composed by [[Ansell Collins]] and named after the film.\n* The episode [[List of Magnum, P.I. episodes#ep41|\"Did You See The Sunrise?\"]] (1982), of the television series ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'', opens with ''Stalag 17'' playing on the TV, as the main character, Thomas Magnum, is watching and remembering his childhood, and the enjoyment he had with the movie, only to grow up and experience his own wartime imprisonment.\n* An uncredited [[William Holden]] reprised the character of a cigar chewing POW in the 1979 war movie [[Escape to Athena]]. Since he is seen only briefly, it can be presumed that \"Sefton\" made another successful escape while no one was looking, probably with a small fortune in ancient Greek artifacts from the dig.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0046359|Stalag 17}}\n* {{Allmovie title|46409|Stalag 17}}\n* {{ibdb title|1944|Stalag 17}}\n* {{tcmdb title|4237|Stalag 17}}\n* {{AFI film|id=51043|title=Stalag 17}}\n* [http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/stalag_17 Stalag 17] at [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n\n{{Billy Wilder}}\n\n[[Category:1953 films]]\n[[Category:1950s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:1950s war comedy films]]\n[[Category:1950s war drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American war comedy films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Billy Wilder]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Franz Waxman]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Billy Wilder]]\n[[Category:Military humor in film]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoner of war films]]\n[[Category:War comedy-drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1953 film by Billy Wilder}}\n{{About|the film|the punk band|Stalag 17 (band)}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Stalag 17\n| image          = Stalag 17.jpeg\n| caption        = [[Film poster|Theatrical release poster]]\n| director       = [[Billy Wilder]]\n| producer       = Billy Wilder\n| based on       = ''Stalag 17''<br> by [[Donald Bevan]]<br>[[Edmund Trzcinski]]\n| screenplay     = [[Edwin Blum]]<br/>Billy Wilder\n| narrator       = [[Gil Stratton]]\n| starring       = [[William Holden]]<br>[[Don Taylor (actor)|Don Taylor]]<br>[[Otto Preminger]]\n| music          = [[Franz Waxman]]\n| cinematography = [[Ernest Laszlo]], ASC\n| editing        = [[George Tomasini]]\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1953|5|29|UK, premiere|1953|7|1|US}}\n| runtime        = 120 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1,661,530\n| gross          = $10,000,000\n}}\n\n'''''Stalag 17''''' is a 1953 [[comedy-drama]] [[war film]] which tells the story of a group of [[United States Army Air Forces|American airmen]] held in a [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[World War II]] [[prisoner of war]] camp, who come to suspect that one of their number is an informant. The film was adapted by [[Billy Wilder]] and [[Edwin Blum]] from the [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] play of the same name by [[Donald Bevan]] and [[Edmund Trzcinski]], which was based on their experiences as prisoners in [[Stalag]] 17B in [[Austria]].\n\nProduced and directed by Wilder, it starred [[William Holden]] in his [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning role, [[Don Taylor (actor)|Don Taylor]], [[Robert Strauss (actor)|Robert Strauss]], [[Neville Brand]], [[Harvey Lembeck]], [[Peter Graves (actor)|Peter Graves]], [[Sig Ruman]] and [[Otto Preminger]]. Strauss and Lembeck both appeared in the original Broadway production.\n\n==Plot==\n''Stalag 17'' begins on \"the longest night of the year\" in 1944 in a [[Stalag|Luftwaffe prisoner-of-war camp]] somewhere along the [[Danube|Danube River]]. The story is narrated by Clarence Harvey \"Cookie\" Cook. The camp holds Poles, Czechs, Russian women and, in the American compound, 640 sergeants from bomber crews, gunners, radiomen, and flight engineers.\n\nManfredi and Johnson try to escape through a [[escape tunnel|tunnel]], but are shot by waiting guards when they emerge outside the barbed wire fence. The other prisoners conclude that one of their own must have told the Germans. Suspicion falls on Sefton, an enterprising cynic who barters openly with the German guards for eggs, silk stockings, blankets and other luxuries. He also organizes mouse races and various other profitable ventures. Sefton tells the men it is foolish to try to escape.\n\nThe lives of the prisoners are depicted: they receive mail, eat terrible food, wash in the latrine sinks, and collectively do their best to keep sane and defy the camp's commandant, [[Oberst]] [Colonel] von Scherbach. They use a clandestine radio, smuggled from barracks to barracks, to pick up the BBC and the war news.  One German guard, [[Feldwebel]] [Staff Sergeant] Schulz, confiscates the radio in another success for the \"stoolie.\"\n\n\"Animal\" Kuzawa is infatuated with movie star [[Betty Grable]], and becomes depressed when he learns she has married bandleader [[Harry James]]. Harry \"Sugar Lips\" Shapiro gets seven letters at mail call and makes Animal think they are from women. When Kuzawa sees a finance company letterhead, Harry admits they repossessed his [[Plymouth (automobile)|Plymouth]].\n\nSefton bribes the guards to let him spend the day in the Russian women's barracks. The other prisoners conclude that this is his reward for having informed the Germans about the radio. When he returns, he is accused of being a spy.\n\nThen von Scherbach takes Lieutenant James Schuyler Dunbar, a temporary inmate, away. Dunbar admitted to the other prisoners that he had blown up a passing German ammunition train while he was being transported to the camp. Sefton resents Dunbar for coming from a wealthy Boston family. The men are convinced that Sefton betrayed Dunbar, so they beat him up and ostracize him. Sefton then focuses more effort on uncovering the identity of the real spy. During a fake air raid, he remains unnoticed in the evacuated barracks and overhears the barracks security chief, Price, talking with Schulz in German and divulging the means by which Dunbar destroyed the train (a [[matchbook]] with a lit cigarette tucked into the edge to create a time delay). Sefton considers what to do; if he exposes Price, the Germans will simply remove him and plant him in another camp, while killing him could expose the entire barracks to retaliatory execution.\n\nOn Christmas Day, the men find out that [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] men are coming to take Dunbar to Berlin for his sabotage. They create a diversion, free Dunbar, and hide him in the Water Tower. Nobody but Hoffy, the compound chief, knows where he is. The Germans, despite extensive efforts, are unable to find Dunbar. After von Scherbach threatens to raze the camp if necessary, the men decide one of them must get Dunbar out. Price volunteers, but then Sefton accuses him of being a spy. Sefton asks him, \"When was [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor]]?\" Price knows the date, but Sefton quickly asks what time he heard the news. Without thinking, Price answers 6 o'clock and that he was eating dinner \u2014 the correct time in Berlin, but not in Cleveland, Ohio, his claimed hometown. Sefton then reaches into Price's jacket pocket and extracts the \"mailbox\" used to exchange messages with the Germans, a hollowed-out black chess queen.\n\nSefton decides to take Dunbar out himself because he likes the odds this time and the expected reward from Dunbar's family. The men give Sefton enough time to get Dunbar out of the water tower above one of the latrines, then throw Price out into the yard with tin cans tied to his legs. The ruse works: Price is killed in a hail of bullets, creating a diversion that allows Sefton and Dunbar to cut through the barbed wire and escape. A pleased Cookie whistles \"[[When Johnny Comes Marching Home]]\" as things can be seen returning to normal in the barracks.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[William Holden]] as J.J. Sefton\n* [[Don Taylor (actor)|Don Taylor]] as Lieutenant James Dunbar\n* [[Otto Preminger]] as Colonel von Scherbach\n* [[Robert Strauss (actor)|Robert Strauss]] as Stanislas \"Animal\" Kuzawa\n* [[Harvey Lembeck]] as Harry Shapiro\n* [[Peter Graves (actor)|Peter Graves]] as Price\n* [[Sig Ruman]] as Sergeant Johann Sebastian Schulz\n* [[Neville Brand]] as Duke\n* [[Richard Erdman]] as \"Hoffy\" Hoffman\n* Michael Moore as Manfredi\n* [[Peter Baldwin (director)|Peter Baldwin]] as Johnson\n* Robinson Stone as Joey\n* Robert Shawley as \"Blondie\" Peterson\n* [[William Pierson]] as Marko the Mailman\n* [[Gil Stratton]] as Clarence Harvey \"Cookie\" Cook (Narrator)\n* [[Jay Lawrence (actor)|Jay Lawrence]] as Bagradian\n* [[Erwin Kalser]] as Geneva Man\n* [[Edmund Trzcinski]] as himself/\"Triz\"\n* [[Paul Salata]] as Prisoner with Beard (uncredited)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Original Broadway production===\nThe film was adapted by Wilder and [[Edwin Blum]] from the Broadway play by [[Donald Bevan]] and [[Edmund Trzcinski]] which was based on their experiences as prisoners in [[Stalag]] 17B in [[Austria]]. Trzcinski appears in the film as a prisoner.\n\nThe play was directed by [[Jos\u00e9 Ferrer]] and was the Broadway debut of [[John Ericson]] as Sefton. First presented at the Edwin Burke Memorial Theater of [[The Lambs]], a theatrical club, on March 11, 1951 (staged by the authors). It began its Broadway run in May 1951 and continued for 472 performances. The character Sefton was loosely based on Joe Palazzo, a flier in Trzcinski's prisoner-of-war barracks. The script was rewritten extensively by Wilder and Blum.\n\n===Casting===\nBoth [[Charlton Heston]] and [[Kirk Douglas]] were considered for the role of Sefton.<ref name=\"Capua2009\">{{cite book|last=Capua|first=Michelangelo|title=William Holden: A Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uMp6ACb74UkC&pg=PA65|date=9 October 2009|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5550-8|page=65}}</ref>\n\n===Location===\nThe prison camp set was built on the John Show Ranch in [[Woodland Hills, California|Woodland Hills]], on the southwestern edge of the [[San Fernando Valley]].<ref name=\"Rowan\">{{cite book|last=Rowan|first=Terry|title=World War II Goes to the Movies & Television Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OdvGBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA443|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-105-58602-6|page=443}}</ref> The shoot began in February 1952, during the rainy season in California, providing plenty of mud for the camp compound.<ref name=\"Phillips2010\">{{cite book|last=Phillips|first=Gene|title=Some Like It Wilder: The Life and Controversial Films of Billy Wilder|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5uohNoRFkwIC&pg=PT163|date=5 February 2010|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0-8131-7367-1|page=163}}</ref> It is now the location of a [[meetinghouse]] of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]].\n\n===Filming and release===\nThe film was shot in chronological order, an unusual practice as that method is usually much more expensive and time-consuming. In a [[featurette]] released later, members of the cast said that they themselves did not know the identity of the informant until the last three days of shooting.\n\nPeter Graves recalled the film was held from release for over a year due to Paramount Pictures not believing anyone would be interested in seeing a film about prisoners of war. The 1953 release of American POWs from the [[Korean War]] led Paramount to release it on an [[exploitation film|exploitation]] angle.<ref>p.146 Weaver, Tom ''Peter Graves Interview'' in ''Earth Vs. the Sci-fi Filmmakers: 20 Interviews'' McFarland, 1 Jan 2005</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Stalag 17'' was a commercial success. Produced on a budget of $1,661,530, it earned $3.3 million in US [[Gross rental|theatrical rentals]]<ref>'The Top Box Office Hits of 1953', ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', January 13, 1954.</ref> and $10 million in worldwide markets. The film was well received and is considered, along with ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' and ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]'' (also starring Holden), among the best [[World War II]] [[Prisoner of War]] films. [[Bosley Crowther]] praised the film, calling it \"cracker jack movie entertainment\".<ref name=NYTCrowther1953>{{cite news |last=Crowther |first=Bosley |title=TWO NEW FILMS ARRIVE; 'Stalag 17' Emerges as Taut Film With William Holden -- Has Bow at Astor |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C03E7D91F3DE03ABC4A53DFB1668388649EDE |date=July 2, 1953 |department=Movies |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> More recently, film critic [[James Berardinelli]] stated that \"among the 20th century directors, few were more versatile than Billy Wilder\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Berardinelli |first=James |title=Stalag 17 |url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/s/stalag17.html |date= |publisher=[[ReelViews]] |accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> The film currently has a 97% \"Fresh\" rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 31 reviews, and the site's consensus stating: \"''Stalag 17'' survives the jump from stage to screen with flying colors, thanks to Billy Wilder's typically sterling direction and a darkly funny script.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/stalag_17/|title=Stalag 17|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=2 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223022922/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/stalag_17/|archivedate=23 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nHolden won the Academy Award for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]. His acceptance speech is one of the shortest on record (\"thank you, thank you\"); the TV broadcast had a strict cutoff time which forced Holden's quick remarks. The frustrated Holden personally paid for advertisements in the Hollywood trade publications to thank everyone he wanted to on Oscar night. He also remarked that he felt that either [[Burt Lancaster]] or [[Montgomery Clift]] should have won the Best Actor Oscar for ''[[From Here to Eternity]]'' instead of him. It is said that he felt he was given the award as consolation for not having previously won it for ''[[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Sunset Boulevard]]''.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nIn addition, Wilder was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director Oscar]], and Strauss for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]].<ref name=\"Holsinger1999\">{{cite book|last=Holsinger|first=M. Paul|title=War and American Popular Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Oe4AOVHkJ9oC&pg=PA310|year=1999|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-29908-7|page=310}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The television series [[Hogan's Heroes]] (1965 to 1971) is based on a similar [[Stalag]]. \n* \"[[Stalag riddim|Stalag 17]]\" is a 1973 [[reggae]] [[riddim]], composed by [[Ansell Collins]] and named after the film.\n* The episode [[List of Magnum, P.I. episodes#ep41|\"Did You See The Sunrise?\"]] (1982), of the television series ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'', opens with ''Stalag 17'' playing on the TV, as the main character, Thomas Magnum, is watching and remembering his childhood, and the enjoyment he had with the movie, only to grow up and experience his own wartime imprisonment.\n* An uncredited [[William Holden]] reprised the character of a cigar chewing POW in the 1979 war movie [[Escape to Athena]]. Since he is seen only briefly, it can be presumed that \"Sefton\" made another successful escape while no one was looking, probably with a small fortune in ancient Greek artifacts from the dig.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0046359|Stalag 17}}\n* {{Allmovie title|46409|Stalag 17}}\n* {{ibdb title|1944|Stalag 17}}\n* {{tcmdb title|4237|Stalag 17}}\n* {{AFI film|id=51043|title=Stalag 17}}\n* [http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/stalag_17 Stalag 17] at [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n\n{{Billy Wilder}}\n\n[[Category:1953 films]]\n[[Category:1950s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:1950s war comedy films]]\n[[Category:1950s war drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American war comedy films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Billy Wilder]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Franz Waxman]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Billy Wilder]]\n[[Category:Military humor in film]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoner of war films]]\n[[Category:War comedy-drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Themoodyblue", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added influence on later Hogan's Heroes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stalag_17"}
{"title_page": "Ira Einhorn", "text_new": "{{short description|American murderer}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Ira Einhorn\n| image_name         = Ira Einhorn.png\n| image_caption      = Einhorn's 1979 mugshot and a 2001 mugshot taken upon his return to the U.S.\n| birth_name         = Ira Samuel Einhorn\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1940|05|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|03|1940|05|15}}\n| death_place        = [[Somerset, Pennsylvania|Somerset]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| other_names        = The Unicorn Killer, The Unicorn\n| charge             = [[Murder]]\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated\n| occupation         =  \n| spouse             =\n| parents            =\n| children           =\n}}\n'''Ira Samuel Einhorn''' (May 15, 1940 \u2013 April 3, 2020), known as '''\"The Unicorn Killer\"''', was an American activist and convicted murderer. He was convicted of murdering his ex-girlfriend, Holly Maddux. On September 9, 1977, Maddux disappeared following a trip to collect her belongings from the apartment she and Einhorn had shared in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Eighteen months later, police found her partially [[mummification|mummified]] body in a trunk in Einhorn's closet.<ref name=compost>{{cite news|last=Melina|first=Remy|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.U_qrdvboct4|agency=NBC News|date=2011-04-21}}</ref>\n\nAfter his arrest, Einhorn fled the country and spent twenty-three years in [[Europe]] before being [[extradition|extradited]] to the US. He took the stand in his own defense, claiming his ex-girlfriend had been killed by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who framed him for the crime because he knew too much about the agency's paranormal military research. He was convicted and served a [[life imprisonment|life sentence]] until his death in prison in April 2020.<ref name=compost/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.6abc.com/amp/ira-einhorn-case-murder-who-was-holly-maddux/6074265/|title=\u201cUnicorn Killer\u201d Ira Einhorn Dies in Prison|work=6abc.com|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis moniker, \"the [[Unicorn]]\", comes from the surname Einhorn, which means \"unicorn\" in [[German language|German]].\n\n==Early life and activism==\nIra Einhorn was born into a middle-class [[Jewish people|Jewish]] family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/schmooze/306565/jewish-earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/|title=When Jewish Earth Day Co-Founder Killed, Composted Girlfriend|publisher=The Schmooze|date=April 22, 2015|last=Cohen|first=Anne|access-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.Vk4u2CtZjYg|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|date=22 April 2011|publisher=}}</ref> As a student at the [[University of Pennsylvania]],<ref name = NYTimes>{{Citation | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html?ref=iraeinhorn | title = Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder | newspaper = The New York Times | date = October 18, 2002}}.</ref><ref>{{Citation | type = background | url = http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,168382,00.html | title = The Ira Einhorn Case | newspaper = Time | date = July 20, 2001}}.</ref> he became active in [[Green politics|ecological]] groups and was part of the [[counterculture]], [[anti-establishment]], and [[Opposition to the Vietnam War|anti-war]] movements of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name = MSNBC>{{cite web|url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922 |title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend | publisher = NBC News | accessdate= 2011-04-22}}</ref>  Einhorn participated in the first [[Earth Day]] event in [[Philadelphia]] in 1970, and later claimed to have been instrumental in creating and launching the event,<ref name=MSNBC/> but other event organizers dispute his account.<ref>{{cite web | publisher = AMGOT | url = http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | type = Letter | author = Earth Week Committee of Philadelphia | title = Einhorn | access-date = 2010-04-25 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017152905/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | archive-date = 2013-10-17 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/04/22/ira-einhorn-not-founder-earth-day/|title=No, Ira Einhorn Didn't Found Earth Day|date=22 April 2015|publisher=phillymag.com}}</ref>\n\n==Murder of Holly Maddux==\nEinhorn had a five-year relationship with Holly Maddux, a graduate of [[Bryn Mawr College]] who was originally from [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], [[Texas]]. In 1977, Maddux broke up with Einhorn and went to [[New York City]], where she became involved with Saul Lapidus. On September 9, 1977, Maddux returned to the Philadelphia apartment she had previously shared with Einhorn to collect her belongings (which Einhorn had reportedly threatened to throw out into the street as trash) and was never seen again. Several weeks later, the [[Philadelphia Police Department|Philadelphia police]] questioned Einhorn about her disappearance. He claimed that Maddux had gone out to the neighborhood co-op to buy some [[tofu]] and [[Bean sprouts|sprouts]], and never returned.\n\nEinhorn's initial [[alibi]] came into question when his neighbors began complaining about a foul smell coming from his apartment, which in turn aroused the suspicion of authorities. Eighteen months later, on March 28, 1979, Maddux's [[human decomposition|decomposing]] corpse was found by police in a trunk stored in Einhorn's closet. After finding the body, a police officer reportedly said to Einhorn, \"It looks like we found Holly,\" to which he reportedly replied, \"You found what you found.\" Einhorn's [[bail]] was reduced to $40,000 at the request of his attorney [[Arlen Specter]]; he was released from custody in advance of his trial by paying 10% of the bond's value, or $4,000. This amount was paid by socialite [[Phyllis Lambert]], one of the many people Einhorn had convinced to support him financially.\n\nIn 1981, just days before his murder trial was to begin, Einhorn skipped bail and fled to [[Europe]]. He lived there for the next seventeen years and married a [[Sweden|Swedish]] woman named Annika Flodin. In [[Pennsylvania]], as Einhorn had already been [[arraignment|arraigned]], the state convicted him ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' of Maddux's murder in 1996. Einhorn was sentenced to [[life imprisonment|life in prison]] without the possibility of [[parole]].\n\n==Extradition==\nThroughout Ira Einhorn's fugitive flight he was supported by the wealthy Canadian Bronfman family,  heirs to the whisky fortune. Others, friends of the Bronfmans, joined them in supporting Einhorn, indifferent to or doubtful of his murder of his ex-girlfriend Holly.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1997, Einhorn was arrested in [[Champagne-Mouton]], [[France]], where he had been living under the name \"Eug\u00e8ne Mallon\". The [[extradition]] process, however, proved more complex than initially envisioned. Under the extradition treaty between France and the US, either country may refuse extradition under certain circumstances, and Einhorn used multiple avenues to avoid extradition.\n\nAlthough Einhorn was not [[death penalty|sentenced to death]], his defense attorneys argued that he would face the death penalty if he were returned to the US. France, like many countries that have abolished the death penalty, does not extradite defendants to jurisdictions that retain the death penalty without assurance that it will be neither sought nor applied. Pennsylvania authorities pointed out that when the murder occurred, the state did not practice the death penalty and so Einhorn could not be executed because the state and federal constitutions forbid ''[[ex post facto]]'' law. Einhorn's next strategy involved French law and the [[European Court of Human Rights]], which require a new trial when the defendant was tried ''in absentia'' and unable to present his [[defense (law)|defense]]. On this basis, the court of appeals of [[Bordeaux]] rejected the extradition request.\n\nFollowing the court's decision, thirty-five members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] sent a letter to [[President of France|French President]] [[Jacques Chirac]] to ask for Einhorn's extradition. However, under France's doctrine of the [[separation of powers]], which was invoked in this case, the President cannot give orders to courts and does not intervene in extradition affairs. Therefore, in 1998, to secure Einhorn's extradition, the Pennsylvania legislature passed a bill, nicknamed the \"Einhorn Law\", allowing defendants convicted ''in absentia'' to request another trial. In another delay tactic, Einhorn's attorneys criticized the bill as unconstitutional and tried to get the French courts to once again deny the extradition on the grounds that the law would be inapplicable. However, the French court ruled itself unable to evaluate the constitutionality of foreign laws. Another point of friction with the US was that the court freed Einhorn under police supervision, as French laws put restrictions on [[detention of suspects|remand]], the imprisonment of suspects awaiting trial. Einhorn then became the focus of intense surveillance by French police.\n\nThe matter went before [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Lionel Jospin]]; extraditions, after having been approved by courts, must be ordered by the executive. The [[French Green Party]] stated that Einhorn should not be extradited until the issues concerning his case were fully settled.<ref name=\"LesVerts\"><!-- this site no longer exists: {{cite web|url=http://www.les-verts.org/article.php3?id_article=224 |title=Les Verts \u2013 Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9 }}--> {{cite web|url=http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|title=Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9|date=July 20, 2001|publisher=Les Verts|language=french|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026202806/http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|archivedate=October 26, 2013|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> Jospin rejected the claims and issued an extradition [[decree]]. Einhorn then litigated against the decree before the ''[[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]'', which ruled against him; again, the Council declined to review the constitutionality of foreign law.<ref name=\"Council of State Ruling\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rajf.org/imprimer.php3?id_article=144|title=Council of State Ruling|language=fr|publisher=Revue de l'actualit\u00e9 juridique fran\u00e7aise|date=July 12, 2001|access-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He then attempted to slit his own throat to avoid imprisonment<ref name=NYTimes2001>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/13/us/france-agrees-to-extradition-of-culprit-in-killing-in-us.html |title=France Agrees to Extradition Of Culprit in Killing in U.S. | publisher=The New York Times | date=July 13, 2001}}</ref> and eventually litigated his case before the European Court of Human Rights, which also ruled against him. On July 20, 2001, Einhorn was extradited to the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html|title=Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder|date=October 18, 2002|work=AP|via=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Trial and penalty===\nTaking the stand in his own defense, Einhorn claimed that Maddux was murdered by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who attempted to frame him due to his \"investigations\" into the [[Cold War]] and \"[[Psionics|psychotronics]]\".<ref name=Salon>{{cite web |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |title=Dave Lindorff's 2002 article on the Einhorn trial in ''Salon'' |accessdate=March 31, 2010 |date=October 18, 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831230541/http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |archivedate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> After two hours of deliberation, the jury convicted Einhorn on October 17, 2002, concluding the month-long trial.<ref name=NYTimes/> The following day, he was sentenced to a mandatory life term without the possibility of parole.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thedp.com/index.php/article/2002/10/einhorn_sentenced_to_life_in_prison |title=Einhorn sentenced to life in prison |work=The Daily Pennsylvanian |first=Stephanie |last=Steward |date=October 18, 2002 |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Einhorn began serving his sentence at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Houtzdale|SCI Houtzdale]]. In April 2016, he was transferred to [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Laurel Highlands|SCI Laurel Highlands]], a minimum security prison that provides care for inmates with health needs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inmatelocator.cor.pa.gov/|title=Inmate Locator|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia|Biography}}\n* [[Crime in Philadelphia]]\n* ''[[The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer]]''\n*[[Earth Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Einhorn, Ira. ''78-187880''. (1972) {{ISBN|0-385-06387-3}} Its title is its Library of Congress number.\n*Einhorn, Ira. (August 2005). ''Prelude to Intimacy''. {{ISBN|1-4116-4911-7}}. Einhorn's account of his life underground from the time he fled the United States in early January 1981 until he met his Swedish wife, Annika, in November 1987.\n*[[Steven Levy|Levy, Steven]]. (1988). ''The Unicorn's Secret: Murder in the Age of Aquarius''. {{ISBN|0-13-937830-8}}. Published while Einhorn's whereabouts were unknown.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217203506/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/lkl8d2.htm Excerpt from Larry King Live] about Einhorn's attempts at denying extradition\n* [http://www.philly.com/philly/hp/art/history_philadelphia_crime.html?next=3&index=32#photo News Photo of the box containing the victim being removed from the house.] (See photographs #35\u00f737.)\n* [http://www.esquire.com/features/ESQ1299-DEC_IRA_EINHORN \"A touch of Eden\"] by [[Russ Baker]], ''Esquire'' December 1, 1999. A series of interviews of Einhorn in France just prior to his extradition.\n* {{IMDb name|1527575}}\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0189593/ The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer] 1999 Movie about Ira Einhorn\n* Documentary series from Court TV (now TruTV) [https://web.archive.org/web/20171006212244/http://filmrise.com/mugshots-ira-einhorn-the-unicorn/ \"MUGSHOTS: Ira Einhorn - The Unicorn\"] episode at ''[[FilmRise]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Einhorn, Ira}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Activists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Central High School (Philadelphia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People extradited to the United States]]\n[[Category:People extradited from France]]\n[[Category:People convicted in absentia]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American murderer}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Ira Einhorn\n| image_name         = Ira Einhorn.png\n| image_caption      = Einhorn's 1979 mugshot and a 2001 mugshot taken upon his return to the U.S.\n| birth_name         = Ira Samuel Einhorn\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1940|05|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|03|1940|05|15}}\n| death_place        = [[Somerset, Pennsylvania|Somerset]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| other_names        = The Unicorn Killer, The Unicorn\n| charge             = [[Murder]]\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated\n| occupation         =  \n| spouse             =\n| parents            =\n| children           =\n}}\n'''Ira Samuel Einhorn''' (May 15, 1940 \u2013 April 3, 2020), known as '''\"The Unicorn Killer\"''', was an American activist and convicted murderer. He was convicted of murdering his ex-girlfriend, Holly Maddux. On September 9, 1977, Maddux disappeared following a trip to collect her belongings from the apartment she and Einhorn had shared in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Eighteen months later, police found her partially [[mummification|mummified]] body in a trunk in Einhorn's closet.<ref name=compost>{{cite news|last=Melina|first=Remy|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.U_qrdvboct4|agency=NBC News|date=2011-04-21}}</ref>\n\nAfter his arrest, Einhorn fled the country and spent twenty-three years in [[Europe]] before being [[extradition|extradited]] to the US. He took the stand in his own defense, claiming his ex-girlfriend had been killed by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who framed him for the crime because he knew too much about the agency's paranormal military research. He was convicted and served a [[life imprisonment|life sentence]] until his death in prison in April 2020.<ref name=compost/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.6abc.com/amp/ira-einhorn-case-murder-who-was-holly-maddux/6074265/|title=\u201cUnicorn Killer\u201d Ira Einhorn Dies in Prison|work=6abc.com|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis moniker, \"the [[Unicorn]]\", comes from the surname Einhorn, which means \"unicorn\" in [[German language|German]].\n\n==Early life and activism==\nIra Einhorn was born into a middle-class [[Jewish people|Jewish]] family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/schmooze/306565/jewish-earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/|title=When Jewish Earth Day Co-Founder Killed, Composted Girlfriend|publisher=The Schmooze|date=April 22, 2015|last=Cohen|first=Anne|access-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/earth-day-co-founder-killed-composted-girlfriend/#.Vk4u2CtZjYg|title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend|date=22 April 2011|publisher=}}</ref> As a student at the [[University of Pennsylvania]],<ref name = NYTimes>{{Citation | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html?ref=iraeinhorn | title = Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder | newspaper = The New York Times | date = October 18, 2002}}.</ref><ref>{{Citation | type = background | url = http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,168382,00.html | title = The Ira Einhorn Case | newspaper = Time | date = July 20, 2001}}.</ref> he became active in [[Green politics|ecological]] groups and was part of the [[counterculture]], [[anti-establishment]], and [[Opposition to the Vietnam War|anti-war]] movements of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name = MSNBC>{{cite web|url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42711922 |title=Earth Day co-founder killed, composted girlfriend | publisher = NBC News | accessdate= 2011-04-22}}</ref>  Einhorn participated in the first [[Earth Day]] event in [[Philadelphia]] in 1970, and later claimed to have been instrumental in creating and launching the event,<ref name=MSNBC/> but other event organizers dispute his account.<ref>{{cite web | publisher = AMGOT | url = http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | type = Letter | author = Earth Week Committee of Philadelphia | title = Einhorn | access-date = 2010-04-25 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017152905/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/eday.htm | archive-date = 2013-10-17 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/04/22/ira-einhorn-not-founder-earth-day/|title=No, Ira Einhorn Didn't Found Earth Day|date=22 April 2015|publisher=phillymag.com}}</ref>\n\n==Murder of Holly Maddux==\nEinhorn had a five-year relationship with Holly Maddux, a graduate of [[Bryn Mawr College]] who was originally from [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], [[Texas]]. In 1977, Maddux broke up with Einhorn and went to [[New York City]], where she became involved with Saul Lapidus. On September 9, 1977, Maddux returned to the Philadelphia apartment she had previously shared with Einhorn to collect her belongings (which Einhorn had reportedly threatened to throw out into the street as trash) and was never seen again. Several weeks later, the [[Philadelphia Police Department|Philadelphia police]] questioned Einhorn about her disappearance. He claimed that Maddux had gone out to the neighborhood co-op to buy some [[tofu]] and [[Bean sprouts|sprouts]], and never returned.\n\nEinhorn's initial [[alibi]] came into question when his neighbors began complaining about a foul smell coming from his apartment, which in turn aroused the suspicion of authorities. Eighteen months later, on March 28, 1979, Maddux's [[human decomposition|decomposing]] corpse was found by police in a trunk stored in Einhorn's closet. After finding the body, a police officer reportedly said to Einhorn, \"It looks like we found Holly,\" to which he reportedly replied, \"You found what you found.\" Einhorn's [[bail]] was reduced to $40,000 at the request of his attorney [[Arlen Specter]]; he was released from custody in advance of his trial by paying 10% of the bond's value, or $4,000. This amount was paid by socialite [[Phyllis Lambert]], one of the many people Einhorn had convinced to support him financially.\n\nIn 1981, just days before his murder trial was to begin, Einhorn skipped bail and fled to [[Europe]]. He lived there for the next seventeen years and married a [[Sweden|Swedish]] woman named Annika Flodin. In [[Pennsylvania]], as Einhorn had already been [[arraignment|arraigned]], the state convicted him ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' for Maddux's murder in 1996. Einhorn was sentenced to [[life imprisonment|life in prison]] without the possibility of [[parole]].\n\n==Extradition==\nThroughout Ira Einhorn's fugitive flight he was supported by the wealthy Canadian Bronfman family,  heirs to the whisky fortune. Others, friends of the Bronfmans, joined them in supporting Einhorn, indifferent to or doubtful of his murder of his ex-girlfriend Holly.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1997, Einhorn was arrested in [[Champagne-Mouton]], [[France]], where he had been living under the name \"Eug\u00e8ne Mallon\". The [[extradition]] process, however, proved more complex than initially envisioned. Under the extradition treaty between France and the US, either country may refuse extradition under certain circumstances, and Einhorn used multiple avenues to avoid extradition.\n\nAlthough Einhorn was not [[death penalty|sentenced to death]], his defense attorneys argued that he would face the death penalty if he were returned to the US. France, like many countries that have abolished the death penalty, does not extradite defendants to jurisdictions that retain the death penalty without assurance that it will be neither sought nor applied. Pennsylvania authorities pointed out that when the murder occurred, the state did not practice the death penalty and so Einhorn could not be executed because the state and federal constitutions forbid ''[[ex post facto]]'' law. Einhorn's next strategy involved French law and the [[European Court of Human Rights]], which require a new trial when the defendant was tried ''in absentia'' and unable to present his [[defense (law)|defense]]. On this basis, the court of appeals of [[Bordeaux]] rejected the extradition request.\n\nFollowing the court's decision, thirty-five members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] sent a letter to [[President of France|French President]] [[Jacques Chirac]] to ask for Einhorn's extradition. However, under France's doctrine of the [[separation of powers]], which was invoked in this case, the President cannot give orders to courts and does not intervene in extradition affairs. Therefore, in 1998, to secure Einhorn's extradition, the Pennsylvania legislature passed a bill, nicknamed the \"Einhorn Law\", allowing defendants convicted ''in absentia'' to request another trial. In another delay tactic, Einhorn's attorneys criticized the bill as unconstitutional and tried to get the French courts to once again deny the extradition on the grounds that the law would be inapplicable. However, the French court ruled itself unable to evaluate the constitutionality of foreign laws. Another point of friction with the US was that the court freed Einhorn under police supervision, as French laws put restrictions on [[detention of suspects|remand]], the imprisonment of suspects awaiting trial. Einhorn then became the focus of intense surveillance by French police.\n\nThe matter went before [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Lionel Jospin]]; extraditions, after having been approved by courts, must be ordered by the executive. The [[French Green Party]] stated that Einhorn should not be extradited until the issues concerning his case were fully settled.<ref name=\"LesVerts\"><!-- this site no longer exists: {{cite web|url=http://www.les-verts.org/article.php3?id_article=224 |title=Les Verts \u2013 Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9 }}--> {{cite web|url=http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|title=Ira Einhorn extrad\u00e9|date=July 20, 2001|publisher=Les Verts|language=french|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026202806/http://www.lesverts.fr/spip.php?page=imprimir_articulo&id_article=224|archivedate=October 26, 2013|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> Jospin rejected the claims and issued an extradition [[decree]]. Einhorn then litigated against the decree before the ''[[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]'', which ruled against him; again, the Council declined to review the constitutionality of foreign law.<ref name=\"Council of State Ruling\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rajf.org/imprimer.php3?id_article=144|title=Council of State Ruling|language=fr|publisher=Revue de l'actualit\u00e9 juridique fran\u00e7aise|date=July 12, 2001|access-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He then attempted to slit his own throat to avoid imprisonment<ref name=NYTimes2001>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/13/us/france-agrees-to-extradition-of-culprit-in-killing-in-us.html |title=France Agrees to Extradition Of Culprit in Killing in U.S. | publisher=The New York Times | date=July 13, 2001}}</ref> and eventually litigated his case before the European Court of Human Rights, which also ruled against him. On July 20, 2001, Einhorn was extradited to the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/us/ex-fugitive-convicted-in-25-year-old-murder.html|title=Ex-Fugitive Convicted in 25-Year-Old Murder|date=October 18, 2002|work=AP|via=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Trial and penalty===\nTaking the stand in his own defense, Einhorn claimed that Maddux was murdered by [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agents who attempted to frame him due to his \"investigations\" into the [[Cold War]] and \"[[Psionics|psychotronics]]\".<ref name=Salon>{{cite web |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |title=Dave Lindorff's 2002 article on the Einhorn trial in ''Salon'' |accessdate=March 31, 2010 |date=October 18, 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831230541/http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/10/18/einhorn/index.html |archivedate=August 31, 2010}}</ref> After two hours of deliberation, the jury convicted Einhorn on October 17, 2002, concluding the month-long trial.<ref name=NYTimes/> The following day, he was sentenced to a mandatory life term without the possibility of parole.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thedp.com/index.php/article/2002/10/einhorn_sentenced_to_life_in_prison |title=Einhorn sentenced to life in prison |work=The Daily Pennsylvanian |first=Stephanie |last=Steward |date=October 18, 2002 |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Einhorn began serving his sentence at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Houtzdale|SCI Houtzdale]]. In April 2016, he was transferred to [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Laurel Highlands|SCI Laurel Highlands]], a minimum security prison that provides care for inmates with health needs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inmatelocator.cor.pa.gov/|title=Inmate Locator|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia|Biography}}\n* [[Crime in Philadelphia]]\n* ''[[The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer]]''\n*[[Earth Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Einhorn, Ira. ''78-187880''. (1972) {{ISBN|0-385-06387-3}} Its title is its Library of Congress number.\n*Einhorn, Ira. (August 2005). ''Prelude to Intimacy''. {{ISBN|1-4116-4911-7}}. Einhorn's account of his life underground from the time he fled the United States in early January 1981 until he met his Swedish wife, Annika, in November 1987.\n*[[Steven Levy|Levy, Steven]]. (1988). ''The Unicorn's Secret: Murder in the Age of Aquarius''. {{ISBN|0-13-937830-8}}. Published while Einhorn's whereabouts were unknown.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217203506/http://www.amgot.org/einhorn/lkl8d2.htm Excerpt from Larry King Live] about Einhorn's attempts at denying extradition\n* [http://www.philly.com/philly/hp/art/history_philadelphia_crime.html?next=3&index=32#photo News Photo of the box containing the victim being removed from the house.] (See photographs #35\u00f737.)\n* [http://www.esquire.com/features/ESQ1299-DEC_IRA_EINHORN \"A touch of Eden\"] by [[Russ Baker]], ''Esquire'' December 1, 1999. A series of interviews of Einhorn in France just prior to his extradition.\n* {{IMDb name|1527575}}\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0189593/ The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer] 1999 Movie about Ira Einhorn\n* Documentary series from Court TV (now TruTV) [https://web.archive.org/web/20171006212244/http://filmrise.com/mugshots-ira-einhorn-the-unicorn/ \"MUGSHOTS: Ira Einhorn - The Unicorn\"] episode at ''[[FilmRise]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Einhorn, Ira}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Activists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Central High School (Philadelphia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People extradited to the United States]]\n[[Category:People extradited from France]]\n[[Category:People convicted in absentia]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ira_Einhorn"}
{"title_page": "Felicity Abram", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian professional triathlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox triathlete\n| name = Felicity Abram\n| image = Felicity Abram 1.jpg\n| caption = Felicity Abram at the World Championship Series triathlon in Kitzb\u00fchel, 2010\n| country = [[Australia]]\n| residence = \n| nickname = Fliss, Flick, Flicka<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|08|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| turnedpro = 2003\n| club = \n| team = \n| retired = 2016\n| pb = World Championships Podiums\n| coach = [[ Shaun Stephens , Craig Walton , Brett Sutton]]<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n| coaching = \n| show-medals = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n[[File:Felicity Abram 2.jpg|thumb|Felicity Abram placing 15th at the triathlon in Kitzb\u00fchel, 2010.]]\n\n'''Felicity Abram''' (born 16 August 1986 in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]]) is an Australian professional triathlete.\n\n==Early life and education==\nFelicity Abram was born on 16 August 1986 in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], to Louisa and Bill Abram.<ref name=\"Triathon 2012\">{{cite web |url=http://www.triathlon.org.au/Assets/Triathlon+Australia+Digital+Assets/Resources/High+Performance/6542+ITU+MEDIA+GUIDE+WC+10-12.pdf |title=Australian Team Media Guide - Barfoot and Thompson World Triathlon - Auckland 14-22 October 2012 |publisher=Triathlon Australia |page = 5|accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref> She spent her early years outside on the family's 20,000-acre estate in [[Central Queensland]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.felicityabram.com/bio/|title=Hi. I\u2019m Felicity Abram.|publisher=Felicity Abram's official website|accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nLater on, she moved to Brisbane to attend [[Brisbane Girls Grammar School]], where she completed most of her schooling , before finishing at [[St Peters Lutheran College]] under athletic scholarship in 2003.<ref name=\"Triathon 2012\"/><ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\nShe was an [[Australian Institute of Sport]] scholarship holder.<ref>[http://www.ausport.gov.au/ais/sports/triathlon/achievements Australian Institute of Sport Triathlon Achievements] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923023655/http://ausport.gov.au/ais/sports/triathlon/achievements |date=23 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<br />\n==Career==\nIn 2003 , at her very first ITU triathlon debut, Felicity Abram won the Gold medal at the World Junior Championships ahead of [[Vanessa Fernandes]] and [[Maxine Seear]] in Queenstown , NZ ''.''<ref name=\":0\" /> .  In 2005, at the young age of 18, she was admitted to the Australian National Elite Team and placed a creditable 6th at her first Elite World Championship . Under the coaching of Australian Shaun Stephens , 2006 marked a highlight in her career with a Bronze medal at the World Championship in Lausanne . In 2006 Felicity also got selected for Australia in the [[Commonwealth Games]] , Melbourne . In 2008 she was the Number 1 in the ITU World rankings, still the Australian Triathlon federation did not appoint her as a member of the Olympic Team for Beijing. Throughout her career she was selected to represent Australia in 8 Elite World Championships ''.''<ref name=\":0\" /> . Other highlights through her career include multiple Noosa Triathlon podiums & multiple FFTRI podiums under French Tri Team TCG Parthenay .\n\n=== ITU competitions ===\nFelicity started in a total 52 [[International Triathlon Union]] races including 12 podiums and 5 wins . The following list is based upon the official ITU rankings and the ''Athlete's Profile Page.''<ref name=\":0\">[http://archive.triathlon.org/zpg/zresults-ath-dtl.php?id=MTc2 Felicity Abram] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320060456/http://archive.triathlon.org/zpg/zresults-ath-dtl.php?id=MTc2 |date=20 March 2012 }},  archive.triathlon.org, 